##Alec Lusher##
##Overview of Client VM Terminal Commands Utilized During Testing##

#Open VirutalBox, create an Ubantu 64-bit VM. Ensure that the VM has 4 vCPUs and 12 GB of RAM. In the Network Settings, select NAT for Adapter 1 and Host-Only Adapter for Adapter 2.
#Once in VM, run: sudo apt update && sudo apt upgrade -y
#Make sure netowrk adapters show by running: ip addr show
#Install used programs by running: sudo apt install openssh-server openvpn easy-rsa wireguard iperf3 wireshark cmstat -y

#OpenSSH
#For the Client, run: ssh-keygen -t rsa -b 4096
#Once the key pair is generated, copy the key over to the Server
#Create the tunnel by running: ssh -L 5201:localhost:5201 vboxuser@(IP)
#In another terminal, run iperf3: iperf3 -c 127.0.0.1 -p 5201

#WireGuard
#Generate Client key: "umask 077" and "wg genkey | tee ~wg_private | wg pubkey > ~/wg_public"
#Once generated, show the key to paste in Server: echo "PRIVATE:"; cat ~/wg_private; echo "PUBLIC:"; cat ~/wg_public
#Run: "sudo mkdir -p /etc/wireguard" and "sudo nano /etc/wireguard/wg0.conf"
#Inside the config file, the following info will be entered:
  #[Interface]
  #Address=10.6.0.2/24
  #PrivateKey=(Client Private Key)
  #[Peer]
  #PublicKey=(Server Public Key)
  #AllowdIPs=10.6.0.1/32
  #Endpoint=(IPAddress):51820
  #PersistentKeepalive=15
#Once the config file is saved, run: sudo wg-quick up wg0
#Ping the server to make sure the tunnel is working
#Once tunnel is confirmed to be working, run: iperf3 -c 10.6.0.1 -B 10.6.0.2
#Shutdown the tunnel once the testing in finished: sudo wg-quick down wg0

#OpenVPN
#Create an openVPN file on the Client VM
#Copy the ovpn-ca files from the Server to the Client
#Once the file paths are built, write to the server config file: sudo nano /etc/openvpn/server/server.conf
  #client
  #dev tun
  #proto udp
  #remote (IP) 1195
  #resolv-retry infinite
  #nobind
  #persist-key
  #persist-tun
  #remote-cert-tls server
  #auth SHA256
  #data-ciphers AES-256-GCM:AES-128-GCM:CHACHA20-POLY1305
  #data-ciphers-fallback AES-256-CBC
  #tls-crypt ta.key
  #ca ca.crt
  #cert client1.crt
  #key client1.key
  #verb 4
#Start the Client: sudo openvpn --config ~/openvpn/client1.ovpn\
#In a different terminal, run: "ip addr show tun0" and "iperf3 -c 10.8.0.1 -t 10"
